  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Current state: 0% coverage.** No test files, no `pytest`/`conftest.py`, no test dependency in `requirements.txt`, and the CI workflow (`.github/workflows/scrape.yaml`) runs the scraper directly with no test gate. ~1,500 lines across 8 modules, all untested.\n\n### Recommended setup (do this first)\n```\nrequirements-dev.txt: pytest, pytest-asyncio, freezegun\n```\n`fetchers.py` even says in its docstring: *\"The HTTP client is injectable so the parsing logic is unit-testable against mocked transports without touching the network\"* — that intent was never followed through. Use `httpx.MockTransport` for all fetcher tests; never hit real ATS endpoints.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — fully untested\n\n**`parse_posted_at`** — the highest-value target: it's the one function every source's messy timestamp format flows through.\n\nGaps: empty string, `None`-like falsy input, millisecond epoch vs second epoch boundary (the `>= 1e12` branch), negative/malformed numeric strings, ISO string with `Z`, ISO string already tz-aware, malformed non-numeric non-ISO string (`\"Posted 3 Days Ago\"` — this is what Workday actually sends and it must return `None`, not raise).\n\n```python\n# test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom models import parse_posted_at, Job\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected\", [\n    (\"\", None),\n    (None, None),\n    (\"1643241332430\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 55, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # ms epoch\n    (\"1643241332\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 55, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),      # sec epoch\n    (\"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\", datetime(2024, 1, 1, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2024-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\", datetime(2024, 1, 1, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2024-01-01T00:00:00\", datetime(2024, 1, 1, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # naive -> assume UTC\n    (\"Posted 3 Days Ago\", None),   # Workday prose — must not raise\n    (\"not a date\", None),\n    (\"-1\", datetime(1970, 1, 1, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # negative numeric edge\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at(value, expected):\n    assert parse_posted_at(value) == expected\n```\n\n**`Job.key`**, **`Job.content_hash`**, **`Job.posted_dt`**, **`Job.to_row`** — untested.\n\nEdge cases: `key` uniqueness/stability across field edits (title change shouldn't change key); `content_hash` must change when title/location/url/department change but NOT when `posted_at`/`salary_range` change (this asymmetry is load-bearing for `Store.diff` and isn't documented anywhere except a comment); `to_row` must drop `raw` and include computed `key`/`content_hash`.\n\n```python\ndef test_content_hash_ignores_posted_at_and_salary():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\",\n              url=\"https://x\", posted_at=\"2024-01-01\", salary_range=\"\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\",\n              url=\"https://x\", posted_at=\"2024-06-01\", salary_range=\"$100k\")\n    assert j1.content_hash == j2.content_hash\n\ndef test_content_hash_changes_on_title():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Sr Eng\", url=\"u\")\n    assert j1.content_hash != j2.content_hash\n\ndef test_to_row_drops_raw_adds_key_and_hash():\n    j = Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\", raw={\"x\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == \"g:c:1\"\n    assert row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py` — fully untested\n\n**`_compile`** — word-boundary regex construction. Untested edge case: a keyword containing regex special characters (e.g. `\"C++\"`, `\"C#\"`) must be escaped, not break the pattern.\n\n**`match`** — the core logic has several untested branches:\n- exclude takes precedence over include (a job matching both should be dropped)\n- `locations` is substring match, case-insensitive\n- `cutoff` only drops jobs with a **parseable** date older than cutoff; jobs with unparseable `posted_at` must survive (explicit design choice per the comment)\n- empty `include`/`exclude`/`locations` lists (falsy but not `None`) should behave like `None`\n\n```python\n# test_filters.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef make_job(**kw):\n    defaults = dict(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Software Engineer\",\n                     url=\"u\", location=\"Remote\", department=\"Eng\")\n    defaults.update(kw)\n    return Job(**defaults)\n\ndef test_exclude_wins_over_include():\n    j = make_job(title=\"Senior Software Engineer Intern\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"engineer\"], exclude=[\"intern\"]) is False\n\ndef test_include_uses_word_boundaries_not_substring():\n    j = make_job(title=\"Engineering Manager\")\n    # \"engineer\" should NOT match \"Engineering\" if boundary logic is strict word match\n    assert match(j, include=[\"engineer\"]) is False\n\ndef test_special_regex_chars_in_keyword_are_escaped():\n    j = make_job(title=\"C++ Developer\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"C++\"]) is True  # must not raise / must not be treated as regex\n\ndef test_location_substring_case_insensitive():\n    j = make_job(location=\"San Francisco, CA\")\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"san francisco\"]) is True\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"Berlin\"]) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_unparseable_posted_at():\n    j = make_job(posted_at=\"Posted 3 Days Ago\")\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is True  # can't confirm staleness -> keep\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_old_parseable_posted_at():\n    j = make_job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat())\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is False\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_builds_cutoff():\n    fresh = make_job(external_id=\"1\", posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n    stale = make_job(external_id=\"2\", posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=10)).isoformat())\n    result = filter_jobs([fresh, stale], {\"max_age_days\": 5})\n    assert [j.external_id for j in result] == [\"1\"]\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` — fully untested, and the riskiest gap\n\nThis is the dedup source of truth; a bug here means silent duplicate notifications or lost dedup state.\n\nGaps:\n- `diff()`: new job → inserted + returned in `new`; unchanged job (same `content_hash`) → only `last_seen` bumped, not returned in either list; changed job (different hash) → updated + returned in `changed`\n- schema migration path (`_migrate`) — simulate an old DB missing `salary_range` and confirm `ALTER TABLE` runs without data loss\n- `get_meta`/`set_meta` upsert behavior (insert then update same key)\n- `added_since` ordering and strict `>` (not `>=`) boundary — a row with `first_seen == ts` must be excluded\n- `count()`\n- context manager (`__enter__`/`__exit__`) closes connection\n- concurrent/duplicate keys within a single `diff()` call (two jobs with the same `key` in one batch — does the second silently overwrite, and is that fine?)\n\n```python\n# test_store.py\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    s = Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\")\n    yield s\n    s.close()\n\ndef make_job(ext_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", **kw):\n    d = dict(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=ext_id, title=title, url=\"u\")\n    d.update(kw)\n    return Job(**d)\n\ndef test_diff_new_job_inserted_and_returned(store):\n    new, changed = store.diff([make_job()])\n    assert len(new) == 1 and len(changed) == 0\n    assert store.count() == 1\n\ndef test_diff_unchanged_job_not_returned_but_last_seen_bumped(store):\n    j = make_job()\n    store.diff([j])\n    new, changed = store.diff([j])\n    assert new == [] and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_changed_job_returned_and_updated(store):\n    store.diff([make_job(title=\"Eng\")])\n    new, changed = store.diff([make_job(title=\"Senior Eng\")])\n    assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n    row = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT title FROM jobs\").fetchone()\n    assert row[\"title\"] == \"Senior Eng\"\n\ndef test_added_since_excludes_exact_boundary(store):\n    store.diff([make_job()])\n    ts = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[\"first_seen\"]\n    assert store.added_since(ts) == []  # strict > , not >=\n\ndef test_added_since_ordering(store, monkeypatch):\n    # insert two jobs at different first_seen, assert oldest-first ordering\n    ...\n\ndef test_set_meta_upsert(store):\n    store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v1\")\n    store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v2\")\n    assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"v2\"\n\ndef test_get_meta_missing_key_returns_none(store):\n    assert store.get_meta(\"nope\") is None\n\ndef test_migrate_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_schema(tmp_path):\n    import sqlite3\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n    conn.execute(\"\"\"CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n        external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n        employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n        first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT)\"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n    s = Store(path)  # should not raise\n    cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n    assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n    s.close()\n\ndef test_context_manager_closes_connection(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"t.db\") as s:\n        pass\n    with pytest.raises(Exception):\n        s.conn.execute(\"SELECT 1\")\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `fetchers.py` — the biggest gap by far (787 lines, 15 ATS integrations, all untested)\n\n#### 4a. `_request` retry/backoff — no test at all\nThis is the piece most likely to hide a real bug (e.g. retrying on a *non*-retryable 4xx, or not retrying a 503).\n\n```python\n# test_fetchers_request.py\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom fetchers import _request, _get_json\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_retries_on_503_then_succeeds(monkeypatch):\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        if calls[\"n\"] < 3:\n            return httpx.Response(503)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        monkeypatch.setattr(\"asyncio.sleep\", lambda *_: None)  # skip backoff delay\n        data = await _get_json(client, \"https://x/test\")\n    assert data == {\"ok\": True}\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 3\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_gives_up_after_max_retries(monkeypatch):\n    def handler(request): return httpx.Response(500)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        monkeypatch.setattr(\"asyncio.sleep\", lambda *_: None)\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"failed to fetch\"):\n            await _get_json(client, \"https://x/test\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_non_retryable_4xx_raises_immediately_without_retry(monkeypatch):\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        return httpx.Response(404)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _get_json(client, \"https://x/test\")\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 1  # 404 is not in the retryable set — must not retry 4x\n```\n\n#### 4b. Every `parse_*` function — zero coverage, and these are exactly the \"field indices are positional/undocumented, defensive access\" functions the codebase's own comments flag as fragile\n\nFor each: (1) a normal well-formed record, (2) missing optional fields, (3) the source-specific quirk called out in the comment.\n\n| Function | Untested quirk from the code/comments |\n|---|---|\n| `parse_lever` / `_lever_salary` | salary present as min/max vs. only `salaryDescriptionPlain`; missing `categories` |\n| `parse_ashby` | `isListed is False` must be filtered out; id fallback `id` vs `jobId` |\n| `parse_smartrecruiters` | location assembled from 3 optional parts, some missing |\n| `parse_recruitee` | location as flat string vs assembled from city/country |\n| `parse_workable` | location as dict vs flat fields — two totally different code paths |\n| `parse_google` (`_extract_ds1`, `_ds1_posted_at`) | malformed/missing `ds:1` blob → `[]` not a crash; job row shorter than expected index; timestamp preference order (idx 12 before 13/14) |\n| `parse_deshaw` | duplicate `data-job-id` dedup via `seen`; missing location/href fallback |\n| `parse_twosigma` | triple-rendered card dedup; location lookup bounded to next anchor |\n| `parse_optiver` | `href` prefix stripping producing external_id |\n| `parse_workday` | `bulletFields` empty → falls back to `externalPath`; prose `postedOn` |\n| `parse_google`/`parse_meta`/etc `raw={\"id\": ...}` truncation | — |\n| `_amazon_posted_at` | malformed date string → `\"\"`, not raise (currently only caught by bare `except`, no test proves it) |\n| `parse_microsoft`/`parse_netflix` | `postedTs`/`t_create` missing → `posted_at=\"\"` |\n\n```python\n# test_fetchers_parsers.py — representative subset (repeat pattern per source)\nfrom fetchers import parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby, _amazon_posted_at, _extract_ds1\n\ndef test_parse_lever_salary_range_present():\n    j = {\"id\": \"1\", \"text\": \"Eng\", \"hostedUrl\": \"u\", \"categories\": {},\n         \"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"USD 100,000–150,000\"\n\ndef test_parse_lever_falls_back_to_description_plain():\n    j = {\"id\": \"1\", \"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"Competitive\"\n\ndef test_parse_ashby_filters_unlisted_jobs():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"isListed\": False}, {\"id\": \"2\", \"isListed\": True, \"title\": \"Eng\"}]}\n    out = parse_ashby(\"acme\", data)\n    assert [j.external_id for j in out] == [\"2\"]\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_malformed_returns_empty_string():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"not a date\") == \"\"\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_missing_blob_returns_empty_list():\n    assert _extract_ds1(\"<html>no data here</html>\") == []\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_malformed_json_returns_empty_list():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', ..., data:[not valid json, sideChannel:{}\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []\n```\n\n#### 4c. Pagination loops — untested (`fetch_google`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_workday`)\n\nEvery one of these shares an easy-to-break \"stop when a page returns nothing *new*\" pattern with a dedup `seen` set. Untested:\n- stops at `max_pages` safety cap even if the server never returns empty (infinite-loop guard)\n- stops when a page returns already-seen IDs only (not just empty)\n- `fetch_workday`'s extra stop conditions (`offset >= total`, `offset > 5000`)\n\n```python\n# test_fetchers_pagination.py\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom fetchers import fetch_microsoft\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_microsoft_stops_at_max_pages_cap():\n    def handler(request):\n        # always return one \"new\" position with an incrementing id so it never naturally stops\n        start = int(httpx.QueryParams(request.url.query.decode())[\"start\"])\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"data\": {\"positions\": [\n            {\"id\": str(start), \"name\": \"Eng\", \"postedTs\": 1700000000}]}})\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_microsoft(client, {\"company\": \"ms\", \"max_pages\": 3})\n    assert len(jobs) == 3  # capped, not infinite\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_microsoft_stops_when_page_has_no_fresh_ids():\n    def handler(request):\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"data\": {\"positions\": [\n            {\"id\": \"dup\", \"name\": \"Eng\", \"postedTs\": 1700000000}]}})\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_microsoft(client, {\"company\": \"ms\", \"max_pages\": 10})\n    assert len(jobs) == 1  # second page returns only 'dup' -> loop breaks early\n```\n\n#### 4d. `fetch_meta` — the most fragile fetcher, zero coverage\nUntested: `\"for (;;);\"` XSSI-prefix stripping, GraphQL `errors` key raising `RuntimeError` with a truncated message (doc_id rotation — the exact failure mode the module comment warns about), token regexes failing to match (should degrade to empty string tokens, not crash), empty `all_jobs`.\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_meta_strips_for_loop_prefix_and_parses(monkeypatch):\n    page_html = '[\"LSD\",[],{\"token\":\"tok123\"}] \"__spin_r\":5 \"__spin_b\":\"b\" \"__spin_t\":1'\n    def handler(request):\n        if request.method == \"GET\":\n            return httpx.Response(200, text=page_html)\n        return httpx.Response(200, text='for (;;);{\"data\":{\"job_search_with_featured_jobs_v2\":'\n                                          '{\"all_jobs\":[{\"id\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Eng\",\"locations\":[],\"teams\":[]}]}}}')\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_meta(client, {\"company\": \"meta\"})\n    assert jobs[0].external_id == \"1\"\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_meta_raises_on_rotated_doc_id_error(monkeypatch):\n    def handler(request):\n        if request.method == \"GET\":\n            return httpx.Response(200, text=\"\")\n        return httpx.Response(200, text='{\"errors\":[{\"message\":\"Unknown doc_id\"}]}')\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"meta graphql\"):\n            await fetch_meta(client, {\"company\": \"meta\"})\n```\n\n#### 4e. `fetch_source` / `fetch_all` — untested\n- unknown ATS → `ValueError` with the sorted list of known ATSes in the message\n- `fetch_all`: one source failing must not abort the others (`try/except` around `one()`); concurrency semaphore actually bounds concurrent in-flight requests; owns-vs-injected client lifecycle (`aclose` only called when client was created internally, not when caller passed one in)\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_continues_after_one_source_fails(capsys):\n    async def handler(request):\n        if \"bad\" in str(request.url):\n            return httpx.Response(500)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": []})\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    sources = [{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"bad\"},\n               {\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"good\"}]\n    jobs = await fetch_all(sources, client=client)\n    assert jobs == []  # both empty, but no exception propagated\n    assert \"failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_does_not_close_injected_client():\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(lambda r: httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": []})))\n    await fetch_all([], client=client)\n    assert not client.is_closed\n    await client.aclose()\n\nasync def test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises_value_error():\n    import pytest\n    from fetchers import fetch_source\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        await fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"bogus\"})\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `pipeline.py` — fully untested\n\nUntested: `load_config` defaults (`sources`, `filters`, `db`, `concurrency` fill in when absent from YAML); `run()` dry-run path returns `{\"matched\": N, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}` **without touching the store** (verify `Store` isn't even instantiated, e.g. via `monkeypatch`/mock, since a bug here would corrupt dedup state on a dry run); normal path calls `store.diff` then `dispatch`.\n\n```python\n# test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom pipeline import load_config, run\n\ndef test_load_config_fills_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"cfg.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n    cfg = load_config(cfg_path)\n    assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {} and cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\" and cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_dry_run_never_touches_store(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"cfg.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {tmp_path/'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", lambda *a, **k: [])\n    called = {\"store_opened\": False}\n    class BoomStore:\n        def __init__(self, *a, **k): called[\"store_opened\"] = True\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.Store\", BoomStore)\n    result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 0, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n    assert called[\"store_opened\"] is False\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. `notify.py` — fully untested, including real error-handling gaps\n\n**`dispatch`** wraps each notifier in `try/except Exception` — this is the one spot in the codebase explicitly designed for fault isolation (one bad webhook shouldn't kill SMS), and it has no test proving that isolation actually works.\n\n```python\n# test_notify.py\nfrom notify import dispatch, notify_console, _sms_body, notify_sms\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef make_job(**kw):\n    d = dict(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\")\n    d.update(kw); return Job(**d)\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"webhook down\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"notify.NOTIFIERS\", [boom, notify_console])\n    dispatch([make_job()], [])\n    out = capsys.readouterr().out\n    assert \"notifier boom failed\" in out\n    assert \"NEW listing\" in out  # console still ran\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_without_env_var(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    from notify import notify_slack\n    notify_slack([make_job()], [])  # must not raise, must not attempt HTTP\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_no_jobs(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n    from notify import notify_slack\n    notify_slack([], [])  # no jobs -> should not POST even though URL is set\n\ndef test_sms_body_ascii_only_and_truncates(monkeypatch):\n    jobs = [make_job(external_id=str(i), title=f\"Job {i}\") for i in range(12)]\n    body = _sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"•\" not in body and \"…\" not in body\n    assert \"+4 more\" in body\n\ndef test_notify_sms_requires_all_four_env_vars(monkeypatch):\n    for k in (\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"TWILIO_FROM\", \"TWILIO_TO\"):\n        monkeypatch.delenv(k, raising=False)\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")  # only one set\n    notify_sms([make_job()], [])  # must no-op, not raise KeyError\n\ndef test_notify_sms_raises_on_twilio_error(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"tok\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_FROM\", \"+1\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_TO\", \"+2\")\n    import httpx\n    def raiser(*a, **k):\n        req = httpx.Request(\"POST\", \"https://api.twilio.com/x\")\n        return httpx.Response(401, request=req)\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"httpx.post\", raiser)\n    import pytest\n    with pytest.raises(httpx.HTTPStatusError):\n        notify_sms([make_job()], [])  # raise_for_status must surface bad creds\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py` — fully untested; several pure-logic functions are cheap wins\n\n**`cmd_db_new`** truncation logic — the trickiest part of the file: it only truncates at `first_seen` group boundaries so a batch isn't split mid-timestamp-group, and it must never advance past `since` if `rows` is empty. No test exercises the `groupby` truncation boundary math.\n\n**`cmd_db_mark`** — validates ISO timestamp, rejects garbage, `--now` vs positional `watermark` mutual handling.\n\n**`_normalize_ats`** — pure string function, easy high-value target: must not touch text inside `<style>`/`<script>` tags or inside tag attributes, only body text between tags.\n\n```python\n# test_agent.py\nfrom agent import _normalize_ats\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\nimport subprocess\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_replaces_smart_quotes_in_body_text():\n    html = \"<p>“Hello” — world</p>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert '\"Hello\" - world' in out\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_skips_style_and_script_blocks():\n    html = \"<style>content: '\\u2014';</style><p>real \\u2014 dash</p>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert \"\\u2014\" in out.split(\"</style>\")[0]  # untouched inside <style>\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1  # only the <p> occurrence counted\n\ndef test_cmd_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary(tmp_path, capsys):\n    # seed store with two first_seen groups where the 2nd group would exceed --limit\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as s:\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"A\", url=\"u\")])\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"2\", title=\"B\", url=\"u\"),\n                Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"3\", title=\"C\", url=\"u\")])\n    from agent import cmd_db_new\n    import json\n    cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--limit\", \"1\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"truncated\"] is True\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 1  # only the first group kept, not split\n\ndef test_cmd_db_mark_rejects_non_iso_watermark(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    from agent import cmd_db_mark\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-date\", \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_pdf_render_missing_input_file_returns_2(tmp_path, capsys):\n    from agent import cmd_pdf_render\n    rc = cmd_pdf_render([str(tmp_path / \"nope.html\")])\n    assert rc == 2\n```\n\n---\n\n### 8. `cli.py` — untested\nJust needs a smoke test that `--dry-run` is threaded through to `run_sync`, and that `-c/--config` default is `sources.yaml`.\n\n```python\ndef test_main_passes_dry_run_flag(monkeypatch):\n    calls = {}\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"cli.run_sync\", lambda cfg, dry_run: calls.update(cfg=cfg, dry_run=dry_run))\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"cli.py\", \"--dry-run\"])\n    from cli import main\n    main()\n    assert calls == {\"cfg\": \"sources.yaml\", \"dry_run\": True}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 9. Integration test gaps (no unit test can catch these)\n\n1. **End-to-end pipeline**: fetch (mocked transport) → filter → `Store.diff` → `dispatch` → assert the right jobs reach `notify_console` output, using a real (tmp-file) SQLite store, run twice to prove the second run correctly classifies new/changed/unchanged.\n2. **`agent.py db-new` → `db-mark` cycle** against a real pipeline run: verify the marker only advances to the watermark actually processed, and a crash between `db-new` and `db-mark` doesn't lose or duplicate rows on the next `db-new`.\n3. **Config → fetchers wiring**: a `sources.yaml` entry with `ats: workday` missing required keys (`host`/`tenant`/`site`) should fail with a clear `KeyError`/message, not a silent empty result — currently `fetch_all` swallows *all* exceptions per-source, so a misconfigured source degrades to \"0 jobs found\" with only a printed line, never surfaced to CI. Worth an integration test asserting the failure is at least logged.\n4. **`store.py` schema migration** against a snapshot of a genuinely pre-`salary_range` `jobs.db` (or the committed `jobs.db` itself, copied to `tmp_path`) rather than a synthetic legacy table.\n\n### Priority order if coverage is added incrementally\n1. `models.py::parse_posted_at` + `Job.content_hash` — everything else depends on these being correct.\n2. `store.py::diff` — silent dedup bugs are invisible until duplicate notifications ship.\n3. `filters.py::match` cutoff/exclude-precedence logic.\n4. `fetchers.py` parsers for the ATSes actually configured in `sources.yaml` (check that file — Microsoft/Netflix/Amazon per the recent commits are highest priority since they're newest and least battle-tested).\n5. `notify.py::dispatch` isolation + `agent.py::cmd_db_new` truncation — both encode subtle invariants in comments but nowhere else.\n",
